“The world was about to change forever. And it almost went by unnoticed …"

From "Song of the Stars"— my Christmas story, celebrating the wonder of that very first Christmas. 🎨 by @alisonjay17. 

Writers are often asked where we get our ideas. I got this one as I thought about how hardly anyone noticed when God stepped out of heaven and came down to live with us. But the Psalms tell us that the created order declares the glory of God (Psalm 19 & 65). Then I started wondering—even though people hardly noticed when the baby was born in that stable in Bethlehem, what about creation? Did the animals and the stars sense and rejoice in the coming of Christ the first time? Were they rejoicing when the one who made them came to live with them?

This holiday in the UK 🇬🇧🎁 comes from a time when (sorry to disappoint—it has nothing to do with 🥊 boxing!) “Christmas boxes,” or gifts, were given to tradespeople, servants, and employees. (Excuse me all fellow Brits to whom this is not breaking news but very much old 🎩!) I love Boxing Day because it’s another bonus day to enjoy Christmas. And I love this quote from Mother Teresa — Christmas can come every day. And the very best gifts don’t come in a box. ❤️ Happy Boxing Day! The Book of Hours (and also strawberries and ladybirds and butterflies and flowers)

It belonged to Mary of England, Queen of France (which has to be the most confusing title) and I saw it in the glorious exhibition THE TUDORS. It was my extremely very most favourite. (Along with some other gems I’ll share another time.) Also it’s miniature. Which makes it even more precious and jewel like and impossibly beautiful.

(It’s also sort of a very early and magnificent picture book. So no wonder because then of course they’re my favourite too.)

c.1495-1500; attributed to Master of Claude de France; tempura on vellum

Loved getting to see the William Tyndale statue in London. (As you know, he did the first translation of the New Testament into English — a century before the King James Version.)

Another beautiful thing. When he was at Oxford, Tyndale read Erasmus’ translation of the New Testament. He soon discovered that while all of his intellectual pursuits had invigorated his mind, only the Bible was able to regenerate his heart. 

What hope.

I wandered across a narrow street in lower Manhattan and into a garden. And I found this beautiful mural randomly on a wall. 

I did some investigation and discovered it is a mural in the garden of the church next door. And the church next door happened to be John Street United Methodist Church—considered home to "the oldest Methodist congregation in America.” It was built in 1841. (Earlier structures were built in 1768 and 1817.)

The mural depicts the early days of the church. 

Inside the chapel, below the sanctuary, is the Wesley Chapel Museum. In the museum there are many artifacts depicting 18th and 19th century Methodist history in New York. One such artefact is “The Wesley Clock” (a gift from John Wesley, himself, in 1769)

So now I have to go back and see it all for myself and share with you.

Oh and that’s not all. Here’s what else I read:

“This congregation also lays claim to another pivotal piece of American history: One of the country’s most prominent African American denominations, the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church, originated at John Street in 1796. Peter Williams, a slave, was a cherished member of the congregation who would go on to become the sexton of Wesley Chapel in 1778. After the Revolutionary War ended and his "owner" fled to England, Williams was then auctioned and purchased by the trustees of the Wesley Chapel; he soon repaid them, thus gaining his freedom. Williams would go on to play a role in forming the Zion Chapel in 1800, becoming one of its original trustees.”

Dydd Gŵyl Dewi Hapus! Today is St David’s Day, our patron Saint of Wales. 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁷󠁬󠁳󠁿
 
These are the last words of St David to his loyal follwers: 'Be joyful, keep the faith, and do the little things that you have heard and seen me do.' "Do the little things in life”—or, "Gwnewch y pethau bychain mewn bywyd.”
 
St David was born on the Pembrokeshire cliffs during a wild thunderstorm. He was believed to have lived to 147. He founded 12 monasteries—one of which is now named St David’s in Pembroke after him. St David’s Cathedral is built on the site of the original monastery. 
 
He was even mentioned in Shakespeare (Henry V), and has his own flag (a yellow cross on a black background), his emblem is a dove. Today the Welsh all over the world will celebrate by wearing a daffodil or a leek. But why a leek you cry? Why a daffodil?
 
Legend has it that on the eve of the battle against the Saxons, St David advised the Britons to wear leeks in their caps so they could distinguish friend from foe. It is also a surviving tradition that soldiers in the Welsh regiments eat a raw leek on St David’s Day.

The Welsh for leek (the original national emblem) is Cenhinen, while the Welsh for daffodil is Cenhinen Pedr. Over the years they became confused until the daffodil was adopted as a second emblem of Wales.

So today is all about wonderful Wales. See even more in my stories. And to top it all off... My Welsh father turns 92 years old today. It’s a red letter day! Pen-blwydd hapus, dad! Dydd Gŵyl Dewi Hapus!

Fourth in my “After going to see the Hopper at the @whitneymuseum — everywhere I go I’m seeing a Hopper” (#walkingaroundinahopper) Series: OK so I definitely have Hopper Fever—but here is the next possible actual location of one PORTION of one of his famous paintings. AUTOMAT, 1927.

This adorable cast-iron radiator. 

I found it. It’s in my very apartment. Really. Well. At least it’s mother is. Because mine is taller. But it has the same round bolt thing (technical-radiator-term) at the top and the two layers. And it’s the same colour-ish.

It gets v hot and clunks and bangs and hisses and spits—but I don’t mind. It’s old. It can’t help it. 

Plus I now have an idea of what the soundtrack of this painting might be if we could hear it—alongside the silence which as in all Hopper’s is deafening.

But seriously how lovely is this tiny jewel of a painting of a small radiator? The care Hopper gave and the attention he paid to this small humble radiator is quite beautiful. 

It’s one of the things I love about Hopper. He painted the everyday life ordinary things and in so doing he opened our eyes to see that there is nothing ordinary about anything and it is all miraculous. Like a little golden radiator.

I came to the Cape — and Hopper Mania has followed me from NYC. Because now I’m seeing Hopper everywhere here, as well. So fifth in my “After going to see the Hopper at the @whitneymuseum — everywhere I go I’m seeing a Hopper”(#walkingaroundinahopper) Series: 
OK so I definitely have Hopper Fever— here’s “Corn Hill,” 1930 (His was painted in Truro, though. Mine is of Harding’s Beach—about 45 minutes drive south of Truro.)

I had no idea when I took the photo of this lighthouse on the Cape that the Cape was one of Edward Hopper’s favourite places, too. Hopper first visited the Cape in 1930—and went on to spend 40 summers here!

I read that Hopper’s Truro paintings are an important crossroads in his work. He paints isolated buildings in huge landscapes—that become almost abstract meditations on colour and form. And yet they are still clearly what they are. A lighthouse, a roof, sky, dunes.

Anyway, it’s like I’m wearing Edward Hopper glasses and seeing what he saw. Once you’ve seen a Hopper… But that is what great art does—it trains your eye. Helps you see. Teaches you just what a huge difference there is between looking and seeing. 

Makes me want to walk slower. Keep my eyes peeled for wonder. And be someone on whom nothing is lost as Henry James put it. What about you?

An old General Store. Stepping in here … and straight back in time.

Old fashioned candy counter. A pot belly stove. Old catalog drawers. Wondrous ladder on rollers.

Also (swipe) what about those signs—“working in field south of barn”!

The Brewster Store has been in operation since 1866. The building started out as a church (built in 1852) But the congregation dwindled during the Civil War and they ended up selling the building. In 1866, William W. Knowles, who ran a store down the street, bought the church for $1! He had the steeple removed and the new general store was born.

General stores used to be the only place to get food in town— unless you grew your own or raised livestock. The general store would also buy from local farmers if they had excess excess.

And this concludes this very olde worlde one of my most marvellous #highlyhelpfulhistoricalmoments

And then waiting. Then the pouring. The adding of the milk. Or lemon. The stirring. The drinking. Ceremonies are so helpful because they help us slow down, linger, savour. Be where we are. They also give our hands something to do that frees our mind to wander and imagine and dream and be creative.

So… what about a tea party?

To help you, (apologies to all my fellow Brits who already know all of this) I’ve put together step by step instructions and a list of everything you’ll need to make a Proper Cup Of Tea. Follow the links in my stories to get started.

The Iron Dog stars in a different Hollywood. A cast-iron statue of a Newfoundland dog stands guard over the grave of a little girl who died in 1862 (probably from scarlet fever when she was two).

There are many stories about how the Iron Dog came to be in Hollywood Cemetery, including  the most popular version that it was moved there to keep it from being melted down into bullets during the Civil War.

Whatever the story— it is very poignant and beautiful. And a monument to two of the most beautiful creations—dogs and little children. And their special bond. And an echo of Eden—how it was always meant to be — in the face of what was never meant to be.

I was ambushed by how moving the whole cemetery was—but especially this little grave. 💔

Quick trip to Tuscon and, being a mad British person, I somehow found myself in the high frightfully crazy heat of the middle of the hot hot day in the middle of the Barrio. I was very very hot. But I loved the beautiful historic adobe buildings I found there. And the dramatic stark shadows. And the colours. And this cactus. And that lamp. More in stories.

The Barrio Viejo is the largest Barrio in the US. (Barrio Viejo means old neighbourhood of course you absolutely knew that like I did.) It was built in the mid-1800s largely by Mexicans.

But it came to be considered a poor neighborhood and was undervalued, and neglected and in disrepair for hundreds of years. In 1969, half the Barrio was bulldozed to build the Tucson Convention Center (ugh). What saved the quite large, still-standing Barrio was a small Catholic shrine called El Tiradito. It’s dedicated to an adulterer who, according to legend, was murdered by his father-in-law. The neighbourhood pushed for National Historic Landmark status for the shrine and succeeded, keeping the remainder of the neighborhood intact. How grateful we can be.

And this concludes this rather hot very colourful (in more ways than one) one of these #highlyhelpfulhistoricalmoments

The ancient fishing port and harbor of Cassis, Provence. (I love the two old boats in the foreground that look like they came straight out of a Pissarro or Cezanne or Sisley painting.)

Famous for its beauty. And for being beloved and painted by the Fauves. And for its castle (which you can see in the distance standing high over the harbour). It was built in the 13th century by the Counts of Baux.

(The term castle is not quite accurate. It refers to the ancient walled city of Cassis in which each family had its own residence. The inhabitants went out in the morning either to go fishing or to work the land and returned in the evening.)

Also famous for its wines. The wines of Cassis are white and rosé, and not to be confused with crème de cassis, a specialty of Burgundy which takes its name from blackcurrants (cassis), not the commune.

IMPORTANT PUBLIC SERVICE ANNOUNCEMENT: Parisians call the town of Cassis "cass-eess," much to the ire of the locals, who insist they live in "Cass-ee”.

If that’s not confusing enough Parisians also refer to the blackcurrant liqueur made in Burgundy as "cass-eess" but southern French locals refer to the wine from the coastal country east of Marseille as "cass-ee." 

And this concludes this rather marvellous one of my #highlyhelpfulhistoricalmoments and #highlyhelpfulbotanicalmoments

My favourite front door lamp in NYC. (And maybe ever in the world) By Tiffany.

It hangs over a beautiful building. Where? you cry. 

There is a secret going-back-in-time street on the Upper West Side—where you feel like you’re stepping back into Edwardian New York. The block is on West 67th Street between Central Park West and Columbus and it’s known as the West 67th Street Artists’ Colony Historic District. The eight graceful limestone and brick buildings were specifically designed for artists. They have soaring ceilings, huge light filled rooms, gigantic windows. How do I know? I saw it with my very own eyes because a very lucky friend of mine lived in one for many years. Over the years, residents have included: Noel Coward, Isadora Duncan, Rudolph Valentino, Marcel Duchamp, George Balanchine, Norman Rockwell, Ellsworth Kelly and Mike Nichols. 

And this concludes this artistic rather lovely one of my #highlyhelpfulhistoricalmoments

Magnificently lit, a 20-foot blue spruce quietly rises in the Medieval Sculpture Hall, framed by an 18th century Spanish choir screen. Choral music soars, angels watch from on high, life like figures race to the see the one born to banish darkness and sadness and suffering and sickness and dying. The one whose name is Love. Born to be a light to light up the whole world.

It is a holy oasis in the middle of the busy city. It’s not glittery and showy. It is a quietly magnificent, silently beautiful glorious tree. How fitting for the one who was born not in a palace but a stable. Whose birth was heralded not by princes and kings but by poor shepherds. In the quiet of the night. 

How wonderful that the Met do this every year. Thank you! 

Going to stand and gaze at this tree is one of my most favourite things to do at Christmas—along with Carols from Kings. Sometimes you get both at once and then it is a little glimpse of heaven. 

A longstanding tradition at the Met and—sorry Rockefeller Tree—this truly is the only Christmas tree for me.

(It is a 18th-century Neapolitan Nativity scene, that shows in detail the Mediterranean harbor town’s multicultural population. The choir screen from the Cathedral of Valladolid in the Museum’s Medieval Sculpture Hall.)

A key quality I look for in children’s books: the best ones are those that an adult and a child can enjoy together. There is nothing snuck in to appeal only to an adult/simply to keep the adult’s attention. Nothing that happens behind the child’s back as it were. It is a story that is generous and true and good enough to keep everyone’s attention.

My brilliant friend Richard Peck and me. Taken at Richard’s birthday party a few years ago. I miss him so much. What a rascal. I wish we could sit down together and catch up and laugh as we used to.

Richard was not only a brilliant writer. He was–as anyone lucky enough to hear him will attest–a brilliant public speaker.

Things I learned from him about public speaking (I consider him my speaking mentor)... 

When you give a talk, always remember:

* The audience doesn’t want to know about you – they want to know about them
* You start speaking the minute you get out of your rental car
* Always go shorter than the time allotted to you
* Prepare! Even if you’re on a panel—prepare!
* You respect your audience by the amount of time you spend preparing

These dogs are in good company. Swipe for a look at a bag from an OLDE HAT SHOP – founded in 1676! Locke and Co Hatters (@lockhatters). Here are some fun Hat Facts: 

🎩 Locke and Co is the oldest hat shop in the world and the oldest hat shop in London. 

🎩 Locke and Co was responsible for the invention of the bowler hat. 

🎩 Admiral Lord Nelson wore a hat from Locke and Co into the Battle of Trafalgar. 

🎩 Sir Winston Churchill wore their Cambridge and Homburg hats. 

🎩 Apparently, James Benning, the shop manager for James Lock III, inspired the Mad Hatter character from Alice in Wonderland. Hatters worked with chemicals… that made them a bit mad, hence the phrase “mad as a hatter.” 

🎩 Other wearers of these hats: Oscar Wilde, David Beckham, Charlie Chaplin, Eric Clapton, Douglas Fairbanks Jr, Alec Guinness, Jeremy Irons, Peter O’Toole, Laurence Olivier.

🎩 Mr Pockles surely would want his own Locke and Co hat?
